This article is a Presidential Proclamation by Barack Obama declaring December 3, 2010, as the International Day of Persons with Disabilities. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of ending unequal treatment of individuals with disabilities and promoting their full inclusion and participation in society. It highlights the United States' commitment to protecting and promoting the rights of people with disabilities, including its signing of the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities. The proclamation also mentions the efforts of the Department of State and the World Intellectual Property Organization in advancing international disability rights. It recognizes the anniversaries of the Americans with Disabilities Act and the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act, which have been instrumental in ensuring equal access and ending discrimination against individuals with disabilities in the United States. The proclamation concludes by urging continued efforts to eliminate barriers and ensure equal opportunity for all individuals with disabilities.